# Frontend SSR and VM deployment

## Frontend is always SSR (never static)

- **Use only `@sveltejs/adapter-node`** for the SvelteKit frontend. Do **not** use `@sveltejs/adapter-static`.
- The frontend runs as a Node server in production (systemd). Build output is `build/` (adapter-node); we run it with `node serve.mjs` which loads `build/index.js`.
- Do not add or switch to adapter-static, Vercel adapter, or any static-only adapter. This template deploys to a VM with systemd; the frontend must be an SSR app.

## Frontend proxies to backend

- The frontend **never** calls the backend from the client by URL. All API access goes through the same origin:
  - **Server-side**: `handleFetch` in `hooks.server.ts` rewrites `fetch('/api/...')` to `BACKEND_API_URL`.
  - **Client-side**: Browser calls `/api/...` on the frontend; `src/routes/api/[...path]/+server.ts` proxies to the backend.
- Env on VM: set `BACKEND_API_URL` (or `PUBLIC_API_URL`) per environment so staging frontend talks to staging backend and production frontend to production backend.

## VM deploy layout (two envs per app)

- **Paths on VM** (layout: `/opt/<app>/{frontend,backend}/{staging,production}`):
  - Staging: `/opt/<app>/backend/staging`, `/opt/<app>/frontend/staging`
  - Production: `/opt/<app>/backend/production`, `/opt/<app>/frontend/production`
- **Systemd units**:
  - Staging: `*-staging-*.service` (e.g. `app-backend-staging.service`, `app-frontend-staging.service`)
  - Production: `*-production-*.service`
- Each app has exactly two environments (staging and production). Service files live under `infra/systemd/` and are applied via `pnpm run apply-template`.

## When editing frontend or workflows

- Do not introduce adapter-static or static-only build.
- Keep proxy behavior: `/api/*` must be forwarded to `BACKEND_API_URL` / `PUBLIC_API_URL`.
- Keep deploy dirs as `/opt/<app>/{frontend,backend}/{staging,production}`.
